<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec-directional-derivatives">
  <title>Directional derivatives</title>

  <objectives>
    <ol>
      <li>
        <p>
          Define the directional derivative of <m>f</m> in the direction of a unit vector <m>\uv u</m>.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Compute <m>\pdv{f}{\uv u}</m> using partial derivatives and the Chain Rule.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Relate directional derivatives to the rate of change of <m>f</m> along a parametrized curve.
        </p>
      </li>
    </ol>
  </objectives>
  
  <introduction>
    <p>
      Introduction goes here.
    </p>
  </introduction>

  <ul>
    <li>
      <p>
        Suppose we're at the point <m>(a,b)</m> and we want to find the rate of change as we move in the direction of the unit vector <m>\uv u=(\cos\theta,\sin\theta)</m>. This is called the directional derivative of <m>f</m> in the direction of <m>\uv u</m>, and is written <m>\DS\pdv{f}{\uv u}</m>.
      </p>
    </li>

    <li>
      <p>
        Limit form of the directional derivative:
        <me>
          \pdv{f}{\uv{u}} = \limit{h\to 0} \frac{f(a+h\cos\theta,b+h\sin\theta)-f(a,b)}{h}
        </me>
        If we think of a function of multiple variables <m>f(x,y)</m> as a function with a vector input <m>f(\bv{r})</m> with <m>\bv{r}=(x,y)</m>, we can also write this as:
        <me>
          \pdv{f}{\uv{u}} = \limit{h\to 0} \frac{f(\bv{r}+h\uv{u})-f(\bv{r})}{h}
        </me>
        This last notation also lets us extend the directional derivative to three or more dimensions.
      </p>
    </li>

    <li>
      <p>
        Parametrize the line in the <m>xy</m>-plane:
      </p>
      <md>
        <mrow>x \amp = a + t\cos\theta</mrow>
        <mrow>y \amp = b + t\sin\theta</mrow>
      </md>

      <p>
        Differentiate <m>f</m> with respect to <m>t</m> using the Chain Rule:
      </p>
      <md>
        <mrow>\pdv{f}{t} \amp = \pdv{f}{x}\cdot\pdv{x}{t}+\pdv{f}{y}\cdot\pdv{y}{t}</mrow>
        <mrow> \amp = \pdv{f}{x}\cos\theta + \pdv{f}{y}\sin\theta</mrow>
      </md>

      <p>
        This is indeed <m>\DS\pdv{f}{\uv{u}}</m>.
      </p>
    </li>

    <li>
      <p>
        If we find the directional derivative in the directions of the basis vectors, we recover partial derivatives:
      </p>
      <md>
        <mrow>\pdv{f}{\uv{x}}\amp = \pdv{f}{x}</mrow>
        <mrow>\pdv{f}{\uv{y}}\amp = \pdv{f}{y}</mrow>
      </md>
    </li>

    <li>
        <p>
            How can we relate the directional derivative of <m>f</m> to motion along any parametrized curve <m>\bv{r}(t)=(x(t),y(t))</m>?
        </p>
        <p>
            If <m>\uv{t}(t)</m> is the unit tangent, then we have:
        </p>
        <me>
          \dv{f}{t}=\pdv{f}{\uv{t}}\norm{r'(t)}
        </me>
    </li>
  </ul>
</section>
